name: Three Pairwise Maximums
description:
You are given three positive (i.e. strictly greater than zero) integers

    x
, 
    y
 and 
    z
. Your task is to find positive integers 
    a
,

    b
 and 
    c
 such that 
    x = 
    max(a, b)
, 
    y = 
    max(a, c)

and 
    z = 
    max(b, c)
, or determine that it is impossible to find such

    a
, 
    b
 and 
    c
. You have to answer 
    t
 independent test
cases. Print required 
    a
, 
    b
 and 
    c
 in any (arbitrary) order.
Input The first line of the input contains one integer 
    t
 (
    1 
    ≤ t
    
    ≤ 2 
    · 10^4
) — the number of test cases. Then 
    t
 test cases
follow. The only line of the test case contains three integers 
    x
,

    y
, and 
    z
 (
    1 
    ≤ x, y, z 
    ≤ 10^9
). Output For each test
case, print the answer: "NO" in the only line of the output if a solution
doesn't exist; or "YES" in the first line and any valid triple of positive
integers 
    a
, 
    b
 and 
    c
 (
    1 
    ≤ a, b, c 
    ≤ 10^9
) in
the second line. You can print 
    a
, 
    b
 and 
    c
 in any order.
Example Input 5 3 2 3 100 100 100 50 49 49 10 30 20 1 1000000000 1000000000
Output YES 3 2 1 YES 100 100 100 NO NO YES 1 1 1000000000
